      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe positive E° of +0.340 V means Cu²⁺ is thermodynamically easier to reduce than H⁺, placing copper **below hydrogen** in the activity series. This is why copper metal does not dissolve in non-oxidizing acids (e.g., dilute HCl). Also, the fact that E°(Cu⁺/Cu⁰) > E°(Cu²⁺/Cu⁺) explains why Cu⁺ is unstable in aqueous solution and **disproportionates** into Cu²⁺ and Cu⁰.\n\n> ⚠️ **Source note:** This value comes from standard electrochemistry references (e.g., IUPAC, CRC Handbook). **NIST SRD-46** is a stability constants database for metal–ligand equilibria and does not contain electrode potentials. If you'd like to explore Cu²⁺ **stability constants** with specific ligands, I'd be happy to look those up!",
